A `debounce` function in JavaScript is used to limit the rate at which a function can fire, which is useful for improving performance when handling events like input or scroll. Here's a simple implementation with an example of how to use it:

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait) {
  let timeout;

  return function(...args) {
    const later = () => {
      clearTimeout(timeout);
      func(...args);
    };

    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(later, wait);
  };
}

// Example usage:
// Debouncing a function that logs input value, triggered on each keystroke
const input = document.querySelector('#myInput');

const handleInput = debounce((event) => {
  console.log('Input value:', event.target.value);
}, 300);

input.addEventListener('input', handleInput);
```

In this example, the `handleInput` function will only execute once the user has stopped typing for 300 milliseconds, preventing excessive calls to the function during continuous user input.
